04565nam a22006735i 9780801454615DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014546157 a10.7591/97808014546152doi  a(DE-B1597)478515  a(OCoLC)979743787  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0240002bisacsh1 aGallagher, Kevin P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRuling Capital :bEmerging Markets and the Reregulation of Cross-Border Finance /cKevin P. Gallagher. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b2 line drawings, 19 tables, 5 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Money00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables, Figures, and Textboxes -- tPreface -- t1. Countervailing Monetary Power -- t2. Challenging Cooperative Decentralization -- t3. From Managing the Trilemma to Stability-Supported Growth -- t4. Let’s Not Get Carried Away: Emerging-Market Innovations in the Wake of the Crisis -- t5. The Politics of Reregulating Cross-Border Finance -- t6. Ruling Capital: The New International Monetary Fund View of the Capital Account -- t7. Good Talk, Little Action: The Limits of the G20 -- t8. Trading Away Financial Stability: Reconstructing Capital Account Liberalization as Trade and Investment Policy -- t9. The Future of Countervailing Monetary Power -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Ruling Capital, Kevin P. Gallagher demonstrates how several emerging market and developing countries (EMDs) managed to reregulate cross-border financial flows in the wake of the global financial crisis, despite the political and economic difficulty of doing so at the national level. Gallagher also shows that some EMDs, particularly the BRICS coalition, were able to maintain or expand their sovereignty to regulate cross-border finance under global economic governance institutions. Gallagher combines econometric analysis with in-depth interviews with officials and interest groups in select emerging markets and policymakers at the International Monetary Fund, the World Trade Organization, and the G-20 to explain key characteristics of the global economy. Gallagher develops a theory of countervailing monetary power that shows how emerging markets can counter domestic and international opposition to the regulation of cross-border finance. Although many countries were able to exert countervailing monetary power in the wake of the crisis, such power was not sufficient to stem the magnitude of unstable financial flows that continue to plague the world economy. Drawing on this theory, Gallagher outlines the significant opportunities and obstacles to regulating cross-border finance in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aGeneral Economics. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801454615zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801454615423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801454615/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK